a majority of britons blame bad management rather 
than labor unions for the nations economic woes a public opinion 
survey reported 
the sunday times which commissioned the poll said 60 percent of 
respondents believe management is more to blame than unions 
when asked if unions have too much power 42 percent said no and 
41 percent said yes the first time since 1975 that more 
respondents took the unions side on that question in the poll the 
report said 
britain had a labor government in 1975 it was ousted in 1979 
after a winter of strikes against a pay freeze prime minister 
margaret thatchers conservatives are still in power 10 years later 
after restricting union power to call strikes and to support them 
with sympathy actions 
a majority said most unions are controlled by a few extremists 
and militants but 77 percent said unions are needed to protect 
workers interests 
the polling company market and opinion research international 
said it questioned 1946 adults including 440 union members across 
the country no margin of error was reported 
britain has low economic investment which results in steadily 
falling manufacturing capacity low economic growth unemployment 
ranging up to 25 percent in the older industrial areas and a 
declining share of world markets 
