<TEXT>
drugrelated killings of police officers hit a 
record high in 1988 but the rate of officer deaths to narcotics 
enforcement remains surprisingly low a private study concludes 
according to the study issued sunday by the washingtonbased 
crime control institute 14 officers were killed in drug enforcement 
activities such as raids arrests and serving warrants including 
one who was assassinated in new york 
by contrast killings of police officers have averaged seven a 
year since 1972 when the fbi began publishing narratives on how 
police officers died in the line of duty 
by another measure the proportion of all police murders 
attributable to drugs has risen from 6 percent in 1985 to 18 percent 
in 1988 the report said 
university of maryland professor lawrence w sherman who also 
heads the institute said part of the reason for the increase is the 
increased drug enforcement activity 
estimated drug arrests have set a record each year since reaching 
708000 in 1984 rising to 11 million in 1988 sherman said the 
numbers of police murders per drug arrest rose from 71 to 100000 
in 1984 to 122 per 100000 in 1988 
the alltime record rate of drug arrestrelated police killings 
was in 1976 when 196 officers died per 100000 arrests followed 
by 1980 when there were 189 police killings for every 100000 drug 
arrests 
while the risk of death per arrest is still not as high as in 
the record years of 1976 and 1980 this trend is still an ominous 
one the study said the record levels of drug enforcement 
combined with rising risk levels per arrest suggest that the total 
murders of police in drug enforcement will increase in future 
years 
putting the risk in perspective the report noted that officers 
who make two drug arrests a day 220 days a year for 25 years will 
make only 5500 drug arrests 
career drug arrests may total on average less than 100 for 
the typical officer it said at these levels of drug 
enforcement activity odds of one death per 100000 drug arrests are 
pretty safe bets 
of the killings since 1972 33 percent happened during undercover 
buy and bust operations 32 percent while serving warrants or 
conducting raids and 5 percent were ambushed during 
surveillance or killed to prevent their testimony 
referring to the ambush killings the report said these cases 
are a mere handful compared to the 220 judges and other court 
officials slain in colombia apparently by drug dealers since 1981 
but it is striking that four out of six of these us cases occurred 
in the period from 1985 through 1988 
the study did not count killings outside drug enforcement even if 
the killer was under the influence of drugs was a known or past 
drug dealer or in possession of drugs 
additionally the report did not mention nonfatal injuries to 
officers 
